Here is the analysis for the anonymous endpoint handling HTTP requests to /send-pdf based on the provided index.js.

- Full HTTP request path: /send-pdf
  - There are no path parameters for this endpoint, so it is exactly /send-pdf (no curly-braced parameters).

- Are all HTTP methods acceptable? No
  - The code defines only app.post('/send-pdf', ...). No other methods are implemented for this path.

- Is HEAD acceptable? No
  - There is no handler for HEAD on /send-pdf. Express will not provide HEAD for this POST route unless a GET handler exists or additional HEAD handling is added; the code does not define one.

- Is POST acceptable? Yes
  - The endpoint is explicitly defined with app.post('/send-pdf', (req, res) => { ... }).

- Is OPTIONS acceptable? Yes (via CORS)
  - The app uses global CORS middleware: app.use(cors()). This middleware handles preflight OPTIONS requests for CORS-enabled routes, so OPTIONS requests to this path are acceptable.

- Is TRACE acceptable? No
  - There is no TRACE handler defined anywhere in the code.

- Is GET acceptable? No
  - There is no GET handler for /send-pdf. There is a GET for root (/) and other routes, but not for /send-pdf.

- Is PUT acceptable? No
  - No PUT handler is defined for /send-pdf.

- Is DELETE acceptable? No
  - No DELETE handler is defined for /send-pdf.

- Is PATCH acceptable? No
  - No PATCH handler is defined for /send-pdf.

Explanation:
- The endpoint in question is defined as a POST route at /send-pdf, which handles PDF generation and emailing. There are additional routes for POST /create-pdf and GET /fetch-pdf, but none of these affect the /send-pdf path.
- The global CORS middleware enables handling of OPTIONS preflight requests, so OPTIONS is acceptable even without an explicit OPTIONS route.
- HEAD, GET, PUT, DELETE, PATCH, and TRACE are not implemented for /send-pdf in the provided code, so they are not acceptable for this endpoint.
